[
  {
    "id": "F-001",
    "severity": "Critical",
    "confidence": "high",
    "title": "Unsupported `cook` actions clear the pending solvency check, enabling uncollateralized borrows and collateral withdrawals",
    "locations": [
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:369",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:456",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:474",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:488",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:527",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:538"
    ],
    "claim": "`cook()` marks `status.needsSolvencyCheck = true` after `_borrow()` and `_removeCollateral()`, but `ACTION_ACCRUE` is never handled and any unrecognized action falls through to `_additionalCookAction()`. In the base contract that hook has an empty implementation, so it returns a zeroed `CookStatus` and wipes the pending solvency check before the final `_isSolvent()` gate runs.",
    "impact": "A user can borrow MIM without sufficient collateral by ending the batch with `ACTION_ACCRUE` (or another unsupported action), or withdraw collateral from an already-borrowing position and skip the insolvency revert. This is a direct drain of cauldron liquidity and leaves the system with bad debt.",
    "paths": [
      "cook([ACTION_BORROW, ACTION_ACCRUE], ...) -> `_borrow()` transfers MIM and sets `needsSolvencyCheck` -> `ACTION_ACCRUE` falls into `_additionalCookAction()` -> returned zeroed status clears the flag -> final solvency check is skipped",
      "cook([ACTION_REMOVE_COLLATERAL, ACTION_ACCRUE], ...) -> `_removeCollateral()` transfers collateral and sets `needsSolvencyCheck` -> trailing unsupported action clears the flag -> borrower exits with debt still outstanding"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "F-002",
    "severity": "High",
    "confidence": "high",
    "title": "Deeply underwater positions become unliquidatable because liquidation does not cap seizure to remaining collateral",
    "locations": [
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:581",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:584",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:593",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:606"
    ],
    "claim": "`liquidate()` picks `borrowPart` solely from `maxBorrowParts[i]` and the user's debt, computes the corresponding `collateralShare`, and then blindly subtracts that share from `userCollateralShare[user]`. If the required seizure exceeds the user’s remaining collateral, the subtraction underflows and reverts instead of capping the liquidation to the available collateral.",
    "impact": "Once a position is sufficiently underwater, honest liquidators can no longer clear it. The bad debt stays in `totalBorrow`, the position cannot be resolved, and the cauldron can remain permanently insolvent after price shocks or after F-001 is exploited.",
    "paths": [
      "collateral price drops sharply -> liquidator tries to repay a meaningful portion of debt -> computed `collateralShare` exceeds `userCollateralShare` -> liquidation reverts -> bad debt remains stuck",
      "after an attacker creates undercollateralized debt via F-001 -> any attempt to liquidate the full debt can revert for the same reason, freezing protocol insolvency in place"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "F-003",
    "severity": "High",
    "confidence": "medium",
    "title": "Clone initialization accepts failed oracle reads and can cache a zero or stale exchange rate",
    "locations": [
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:146",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:148",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:158",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:226",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:233",
      "cauldrons/CauldronV4.sol:329"
    ],
    "claim": "`init()` ignores the success flag returned by `oracle.get()` and stores whatever `rate` value comes back. If a clone is initialized while the oracle is failing or returns zero, `exchangeRate` can be set to 0/stale, and later solvency checks will keep reusing that cached value whenever `updateExchangeRate()` cannot refresh it.",
    "impact": "A freshly deployed clone can start life with an effectively broken solvency model. Attackers only need negligible collateral to pass `_isSolvent()` and can drain the clone’s available MIM until the oracle begins returning valid data again, leaving bad debt once a real rate is restored.",
    "paths": [
      "oracle outage or bad oracle response during `init()` -> `exchangeRate` cached as 0/stale -> borrower adds dust collateral and calls `borrow()` or `cook()` -> `updateExchangeRate()` falls back to cached rate -> `_isSolvent()` approves an outsized loan"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "F-004",
    "severity": "Medium",
    "confidence": "high",
    "title": "Privileged owner can assign debt to arbitrary users without transferring them any MIM",
    "locations": [
      "cauldrons/PrivilegedCauldronV4.sol:15",
      "cauldrons/PrivilegedCauldronV4.sol:16",
      "cauldrons/PrivilegedCauldronV4.sol:18",
      "cauldrons/PrivilegedCauldronV4.sol:22"
    ],
    "claim": "`addBorrowPosition()` directly increases `totalBorrow` and `userBorrowPart[to]` for any target address, but it never transfers MIM to that borrower and it bypasses the normal borrow flow’s caps and opening-fee logic. The only safety check is a cached-rate solvency test after the debt has already been assigned.",
    "impact": "A malicious or compromised master owner can saddle users with debt they never received, then liquidate their collateral or leave the system with synthetic debt unbacked by a real loan disbursement. This is a collateral-confiscation primitive, not just a parameter tweak.",
    "paths": [
      "owner calls `addBorrowPosition(victim, amount)` up to the victim’s collateral limit -> victim owes MIM they never received -> owner or an accomplice liquidates the victim’s collateral",
      "owner uses stale `exchangeRate` and assigns too much debt before refreshing the oracle -> victim becomes immediately undercollateralized"
    ]
  }
